Root Node. The main reference node in N4J.
Class Metadata Nodes. They represent actual data model. The relationships between them
build the class and containment hierarchies.
Object Nodes. These nodes are the instances of the classes represented by the class metadata nodes
Attribute Metadata Nodes. They make part of the data model as well, each one representing an attribute within a given class.
Attribute visibility or its type are examples of properties in these kind of nodes.
Dumy Root Node. It's a dummy root used to contain (as in the containment hierarchy) objects. All objects children
of the root node in the navigation tree have a CHILD_OF relationship with it. All the classes whose instances can be
contained into it have a POSSIBLE_CHILD relationship established with it as well.
Category Metadata Nodes. Categories are used to group classes with similar contexts (i.e. Router and Switch classes -represented by their
respective class metadata nodes- have a relationship with "Network Elements" category node)
Interface Metadata Nodes. Mimic the behavior of an OOP interface, just like class metadata nodes do with the concept of OOP class
Very likely to disappear in the future, since the authentication is meant to be
handled outside, integrating identity managers or simple authentication sources
Group Nodes. Represent the available groups (to manage permissions).
User Nodes. Represent the available users (to manage permissions).
View Nodes. Represent the saved views for a given object (tipically -although not necessarily- the way the children of an object or organized
i.e. the rooms inside a floor).
History entry nodes. Used to stored the changes performed on the existing objects
Query nodes. Used to store queries to be executed on demand.
Pools nodes. Used to group objects that normally can't be put under the .conventional natigation tree (e.g. VLANs or IPAddresses)
